      "answer": " According to the provided context, the main differences between viruses and bacteria are as follows:\n\n1. Nature: Viruses are not considered living organisms because they cannot survive or reproduce outside of a host cell. Bacteria, on the other hand, are living organisms that can grow and multiply independently.\n\n2. Structure: Viruses consist of genetic material (DNA or RNA) enclosed in a protein coat called a capsule. They may also have an outer envelope of lipids derived from the host cell membrane. Bacteria, however, are single-celled organisms with a cell wall, cytoplasm, and nucleus.\n\n3. Reproduction: Viruses replicate by inserting their genetic material into the host cell and using the host's machinery to produce more viral particles. Bacteria reproduce through binary fission, where they divide into two identical daughter cells.\n\n4. Response to antibiotics: Antibiotics are effective against bacterial infections but not against viral infections because bacteria have a cell wall that can be targeted by antibiotics, while viruses do not have a cell wall.\n\n5. Symptoms and treatment: Bacterial infections tend to localize to one area and cause symptoms such as pain, inflammation, or discharge. Viral infections, on the other hand, often affect the entire body and may cause symptoms like fever, fatigue, and coughing. Treatment for bacterial infections typically involves antibiotics, while antiviral medications are used to treat viral infections.",
